'''Mohamed Demagh''' (4 July 1930 – 16 August 2018)<ref>[http://www.aps.dz/culture/77566-l-artiste-sculpteur-mohamed-demagh-n-est-plus L'artiste sculpteur Mohamed Demagh n'est plus] {{fr icon}}</ref> was an Algerian sculptor.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vNjgLZ9LPpsC&pg=PA245&dq=mohamed+demagh+sculpteur&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=350UUuzlONS-4AOh44GgCg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=mohamed%20demagh%20sculpteur&f=false|title=Algérie : Arts Plastiques: Dictionnaire biographique (1900-2010)|last=Abrous|first=Mansour|date=2011-02-01|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|isbn=9782296451643|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5cmfAAAAMAAJ&q=mohamed+demagh+sculpteur&dq=mohamed+demagh+sculpteur&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=350UUuzlONS-4AOh44GgCg&redir_esc=y|title=Les artistes algériens: dictionnaire biographique (1917-1999)|last=Abrous|first=Mansour|date=2002|publisher=Casbah|isbn=9789961642931|language=fr}}</ref>

== Biography ==

During the [[Algerian War]] Mohamed Demagh survived a bombing of French aviation in the maquis in [[Aures]] under the command of Abdelhamid Boudiaf (not to be confused with Mohammed Boudiaf) where 35 of his companions perished. He refused to participate in the [[First Indochina War]].

Mohamed Demagh began his artistic career in 1966. He has presented several solo exhibitions and participated in mass demonstrations in Algeria (1972, 1974, 1983, 1992).

After [[September 11 attacks]], in memory of the victims, he created a piece of debris from bombs dating from the [[Algerian War]].<ref>Mr Bourki, El Watan, 3 October 2005</ref>

A retrospective of the artist's life was produced by the Algerian television during the 1980s.

